<div id="review_2329964092" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2329964092" />
    <a title="Evan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1248986-evan"><img alt="Evan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1488574589p2/1248986.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2329964092?book_show_action=true">Jan 14, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Evan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Evan" href="/user/show/1248986-evan">Evan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780394419510" href="/book/show/44243.The_Civil_War">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1248986-evan?shelf=civil-war">civil-war</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1248986-evan?shelf=epic">epic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1248986-evan?shelf=my-faves">my-faves</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1248986-evan?shelf=warfare">warfare</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1248986-evan?shelf=silver-holy-grail-award">silver-holy-grail-award</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1248986-evan?shelf=better-than-the-crap-youre-reading">better-than-the-crap-youre-reading</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1248986-evan?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1248986-evan?shelf=2019-reads">2019-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1248986-evan?shelf=___8000-meter-peaks-of-literature">___8000-meter-peaks-of-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1248986-evan?shelf=history-americana">history-americana</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2329964092" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17403750055454140487">Highest recommendation. One of the great reading experiences of my life.<br/><br/>I&apos;m finding, at least for me, that taking a General Grant-like approach to this series of huge books -- setting a blistering pace and taking it head-on and fast -- suits me more than doing it with the &quot;slows,&quot; <i>a la</i> McClellan, Burnside, Hooker and Bragg, that is, falling back into a slow, defensive-like posture. It&apos;s now or never, I say, so let&apos;s drive on to conquest.<br/><br/>This gargantuan book has been with me all day long, every d</span>
  <span id="freeText17403750055454140487" style="display:none">Highest recommendation. One of the great reading experiences of my life.<br /><br />I'm finding, at least for me, that taking a General Grant-like approach to this series of huge books -- setting a blistering pace and taking it head-on and fast -- suits me more than doing it with the "slows," <i>a la</i> McClellan, Burnside, Hooker and Bragg, that is, falling back into a slow, defensive-like posture. It's now or never, I say, so let's drive on to conquest.<br /><br />This gargantuan book has been with me all day long, every day, consuming my days for the last week; just as with Volume 1 the week before --on my desktop to read when I can; and the rest of the time in my ear voiced with authority by the incomparable Grover Gardner on the library's Playaway Mp3 player when I'm out and about and doing my work and business. This is the secret to getting a massive book done in record time, and, if you're self employed, you can. If not, obviously, you can't.<br /><br />The upshot is this: Volume 2 -- which at 1,000 pages is even longer than the first book -- improves greatly on the first: Foote's writing has hit its stride, the contextual issues of the war and the variety of incident -- political, social, and military -- have all been broadened and the sense of scope magnified. The book covers the titanic year of 1863 -- vintage of the great battles of the war: Gettysburg, Chancellorsville, Vicksburg, etc. And then there are the ancillary adventurers, characters like Grierson, Morgan and Quantrill who pulled off daring and often brutal raids deep into enemy territory -- adventures so rich and eventful that they merit books all unto themselves. The sense of being there is so palpable that you feel like you're in the rooms with Grant and Sherman as they share cigars and strategy; with Lincoln as he pores over the words for the Gettysburg address or devises maneuvers he constantly had to to outwit recalcitrant generals or political rivals. The Emancipation Proclamation and the significance of its meaning come to bear, as does the growing importance of the economic imbalances on the combatants, the looming influences of foreign powers on the conflict, and so much more.<br /><br />In short, this is Foote's masterpiece; one of the finest things I've ever read, and -- quite honestly -- I'd like to start all over, right now, and read it again. It's that good.<br /><br />-kr/eg '19</span>
  <a data-text-id="17403750055454140487" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
