<span id="freeTextContainer10493305096819338093">Finally finished this - it is a great read but so thorough that it is quite an undertaking especially when at times you can&apos;t put it down and it is late at night and you have hundreds of pages to go.<br/>The parts about the main protagonists (Lincoln, Lee, Jackson, Grant and Sherman especially plus the lesser known Nathan Bedford Forrest) and the major battles (Gettysburg, Vicksburg, etc) are fascinating. These three books are about every battle and everything that happened though so there are some m</span>
  <span id="freeText10493305096819338093" style="display:none">Finally finished this - it is a great read but so thorough that it is quite an undertaking especially when at times you can't put it down and it is late at night and you have hundreds of pages to go.<br />The parts about the main protagonists (Lincoln, Lee, Jackson, Grant and Sherman especially plus the lesser known Nathan Bedford Forrest) and the major battles (Gettysburg, Vicksburg, etc) are fascinating. These three books are about every battle and everything that happened though so there are some minor battles and minor characters that are more of a slog to get through. That is why I am not giving this 5 stars although the majority of the book is 5 star standard.<br /><br />I might take a short break and read something else before the final instalment as this has taken me almost a month to read which is unprecedented for me. But I'm definitely going to read it soon. This series has turned me from someone who knew almost nothing about the American Civil War to a real enthusiast and I feel pretty well informed now. Still think that Stonewall Jackson's death at Chancellorsville (ironically after being mistakenly shot by his own troops) was the turning point where it all started going wrong for the South - as I did when I read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18144074.Rebel_Yell_The_Violence__Passion__and_Redemption_of_Stonewall_Jackson" title="Rebel Yell The Violence, Passion, and Redemption of Stonewall Jackson by S.C. Gwynne" rel="nofollow noopener">Rebel Yell: The Violence, Passion, and Redemption of Stonewall Jackson</a> which set me off on this journey to find out more about the Civil War.<br /><br />A big commitment but well worth the effort and something that everyone should try and read sometime.</span>
