<div id="review_3823959107" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3823959107" />
    <a title="Logan Grant" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4635083-logan-grant"><img alt="Logan Grant" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1613701469p2/4635083.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3823959107?book_show_action=true">Mar 16, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Logan Grant" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Logan Grant" href="/user/show/4635083-logan-grant">Logan Grant</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/15981166-the-civil-war">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3823959107" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2852382468332083652"><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/10252346.The_Civil_War_A_Narrative_Volume_2_Fredericksburg_to_Meridian' title='The Civil War A Narrative Volume 2 Fredericksburg to Meridian by Shelby Foote' rel='nofollow noopener'>
  <img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1417982166l/10252346._SY75_.jpg' alt='The Civil War A Narrative Volume 2 Fredericksburg to Meridian by Shelby Foote' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/>
</a><br/>Published: 1963<br/><br/>My background on the subject:<br/>1) The Impending Crisis (David M. Potter, 1976)<br/>2) Grant (Jean Edward Smith, 2002)<br/>3) Lincoln (David Herbert Donald, 1996)<br/>4) Battle Cry of Freedom (James McPherson, 1988)<br/>5) The Civil War: Volume 1 (Foote, 1958)<br/><br/>“Peace does not appear so distant as it did. I hope it will come soon, and come to stay; and so come as to be worth the keeping in all future time— It will then have been proved that, among free men, there can be no successful appeal from the b</span>
  <span id="freeText2852382468332083652" style="display:none"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/10252346.The_Civil_War_A_Narrative_Volume_2_Fredericksburg_to_Meridian" title="The Civil War A Narrative Volume 2 Fredericksburg to Meridian by Shelby Foote" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1417982166l/10252346._SY75_.jpg" alt="The Civil War A Narrative Volume 2 Fredericksburg to Meridian by Shelby Foote" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br>Published: 1963<br><br>My background on the subject:<br>1) The Impending Crisis (David M. Potter, 1976)<br>2) Grant (Jean Edward Smith, 2002)<br>3) Lincoln (David Herbert Donald, 1996)<br>4) Battle Cry of Freedom (James McPherson, 1988)<br>5) The Civil War: Volume 1 (Foote, 1958)<br><br>“Peace does not appear so distant as it did. I hope it will come soon, and come to stay; and so come as to be worth the keeping in all future time— It will then have been proved that, among free men, there can be no successful appeal from the ballot to the bullet; and that they who take such appeal are sure to lose their case, and pay the cost. And then, there will be some black men who can remember that, with silent tongue, and clenched teeth, and steady eye, and well borne poised bayonet, they have helped mankind on to this great consummation; while I fear, there will be some white ones, unable to forget that, with malignant hearts, and deceitful speech, they have strove to hinder it.”<br>				-Abraham Lincoln, 1863<br><br>I usually underestimate the second part of a trilogy. In this case, not only was my doubt grossly misplaced, but my lowered expectations actually enriched the pleasure of an already terrific book. Foote’s ability to organize dramatic historical events into a narrative that nearly follows a traditional story structure continues to amaze me. Equally impressive is his consistency in presenting characters and groups uniquely and sympathetically, but not uncritically. That said, the institutional subjugation of black Americans is still almost completely pushed aside to focus on military and political personalities and events. Nor does Foote present more than a superficial explanation of what is meant by The Cause. After two full volumes The Cause has been presented merely as a broad desire for independence, as if the motivations and objectives of the Confederates were identical to those of the Continental Congress and Continental Army in the 1770’s. I suppose it’s a fair argument; that in the mind of the Southerners, their war for independence was based the same principles as The War for Independence. Perhaps such an analysis is beyond the intended scope of the book. It didn’t ruin the book for me but there were occasions where its absence was glaring. For example, Foote gives a salutary account of John Pemberton’s dedication to the Confederacy which was so thorough that the native Pennsylvanian endured complete disownment from his family to adopt the South as his country and fight for it. However, Foote never explains what inspired or seduced Pemberton to The Cause.<br><br>I reiterate from my review of the first volume that if I had not already read a broad history of the Civil War, Foote’s persistent blind-eye would bother me much more than it does. Someone could no doubt level some legitimate criticism against me for having so little trouble dissociating slavery from a narrative on the Civil War. I have thought about it a fair amount, and I acknowledge that there is an inverse relationship between exposition about the racial prejudices of the characters (both North and South) and the sympathy I am able to develop for them as they battle for their respective causes. I attribute this to my relatively enlightened views on the universality of human character and an innate human desire to focus on the positive aspects of ones forbears (teenage years notwithstanding). Even so, I suspect that to present historical figures largely as they might have presented themselves does not inherently impair or distort the veracity of my understanding of history, but is perhaps an essential element of a multifaceted approach. Anyway, back to the book.<br><br>This installment of the trilogy would serve as a nearly perfect second act if the Confederacy were the protagonists (they are not) and if they ultimately won the war (no spoilers). The first third of the book recounts a number of battles in which the Confederates manage dramatic victories in spite of overwhelming odds against them. Here it is particularly crucial to neglect for a moment some of the sinister motivations underlying The Cause if you want to partake in the excitement of extraordinary triumphs of a vastly outnumbered and underequipped military force. After a handful of these successes, things really start to look up for the underdog Confederacy. Just like gravity, however, the Union’s overwhelming advantages eventually bring them back down to Earth at Gettysburg and Vicksburg.<br><br>Foote’s recounting of battles is enthralling because of his skillful orchestration of entertaining and revealing anecdotes within intriguing subplots within an epic story. Nowhere is this more clearly demonstrated than in his account of the Battle of Gettysburg. The drama, the stakes, and the consequences of that massive confrontation are awe-inspiring to me. Using his talent as a novelist, Foote illustrates how the most seemingly insignificant action or inaction can determine the outcome of the whole contest. That doesn’t go for every battle, however. Some are a fait accompli. For example, the biggest challenge for Grant in taking Vicksburg was simply getting his troops there alive and equipped for a siege, though that challenge was one of the toughest he would face during the entire war.<br><br>After Lee’s army lost so many irreplaceable soldiers at Gettysburg and the Union took complete control of the Mississippi River with the conquests of Vicksburg and Port Hudson, the romantic visions/delusions of independence faded into a hard reality for all but the most faithful Confederate military leaders. General Longstreet explained it well at that time: “[Vicksburg], taken in connection with the Gettysburg defeat, was, of course, very discouraging to our superior officers, though I do not know that it was felt as keenly by the rank and file. For myself, I felt that our last hope was gone, and that it was now only a question of time with us.”<br><br>Many in the Confederacy had known from the beginning that they stood no chance at success against the Union’s vast superiority of manpower, materials, naval power, and industrial capacity. Both Jefferson Davis and Robert E. Lee indicated at the outset that the Confederacy’s struggle for independence would require the intervention of God for success. Beseeching God’s support is always a good practice, but I believe that Davis and Lee might have been speaking more literally than the average Southerner supposed. By the second half of 1863, although their faith in the righteousness of God was undisturbed, their faith in the righteousness of the Confederacy was holding on only by expression of their force of will.<br><br>My favorite part of the book is how it ends. I won’t spoil anything except to say that suddenly everything that has happened in both volumes, which was more often spent in the vantage point of the South, seems like a prelude to the ascension of something both indomitable and inevitable: Ulysses S. Grant.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2852382468332083652" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


