<span id="freeTextContainer14572445079460796120">This second volume is as good as the first, especially since it covers some of the most dramatic battles of the Civil War: Gettysburg, Chickamauga, and Chancellorsville. Shelby Foote&apos;s writing is as good as ever. My favorite passages from this book: <br/>&quot;What mainly distinguished the conflict from the outset was its fury. An Alabamian described the racket as &apos;one solid, unbroken wave of awe-inspiring sound...as if all the fires of earth and hell had been turned loose in one mighty effort to destroy </span>
  <span id="freeText14572445079460796120" style="display:none">This second volume is as good as the first, especially since it covers some of the most dramatic battles of the Civil War: Gettysburg, Chickamauga, and Chancellorsville. Shelby Foote's writing is as good as ever. My favorite passages from this book: <br />"What mainly distinguished the conflict from the outset was its fury. An Alabamian described the racket as 'one solid, unbroken wave of awe-inspiring sound...as if all the fires of earth and hell had been turned loose in one mighty effort to destroy each other."<br /><br />My second favorite, an exchange of dialogue between General Braxton Bragg and a long-suffering private: <br />Do you know what a retreat looks like?" <br />Private: "I ought to, General. I've been with you during your whole campaign."<br /><br /></span>
