    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3641199848" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3641199848" />
    <a title="Steve Scott" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1092285-steve-scott"><img alt="Steve Scott" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1360952257p2/1092285.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3641199848?book_show_action=true">Nov 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steve Scott" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steve Scott" href="/user/show/1092285-steve-scott">Steve Scott</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1092285-steve-scott?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1092285-steve-scott?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1092285-steve-scott?shelf=civil-war-1861-1865">civil-war-1861-1865</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3641199848" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7513966286681864386">In this volume Foote overlooks the murder of black prisoners of war and wounded at the Battle of Olustee, and yet mentions the lynching of a slave by Union soldiers who thought that the slave had betrayed them and thwarted their mission. He also fails to mention the re-enslavement of free Pennsylvania blacks during Lee&apos;s progress towards Gettysburg, and the heinous murder of one who resisted. To be fair, he may not have known about the murder of those soldiers or freedmen, but it confirms a bias</span>
  <span id="freeText7513966286681864386" style="display:none">In this volume Foote overlooks the murder of black prisoners of war and wounded at the Battle of Olustee, and yet mentions the lynching of a slave by Union soldiers who thought that the slave had betrayed them and thwarted their mission. He also fails to mention the re-enslavement of free Pennsylvania blacks during Lee's progress towards Gettysburg, and the heinous murder of one who resisted. To be fair, he may not have known about the murder of those soldiers or freedmen, but it confirms a bias towards the South that Foote himself owned in saying he would have fought for the South.<br /><br />Yet here, as in Volume 1, he seems perfectly fair in maligning the incompetent generals, North and South, whose blundering cost so many lives. <br /><br />Whatever his viewpoint, this series is indispensable and marvelously informative. So much so that after finishing the audiobook, I plan on reading the print version.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7513966286681864386" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


