<div id="review_3360392668" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3360392668" />
    <a title="Stephanie Weisgerber" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/26663263-stephanie-weisgerber"><img alt="Stephanie Weisgerber" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1469925968p2/26663263.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3360392668?book_show_action=true">Jul 14, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephanie Weisgerber" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephanie Weisgerber" href="/user/show/26663263-stephanie-weisgerber">Stephanie Weisgerber</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3360392668" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13664657703874610917">My summer time BIG read is conquered. Hoorah! Book 2 of this exhaustive Civil War trilogy did not disappoint. Shelby Foote goes into extensive detail of many battles during years 3-4 of the war, with particular emphasis on the Battles of Vicksburg and Gettysburg. I especially enjoyed reading of the battle of Gettysburg, as I live in the area and frequently visit the historical sites there with my children. <br/><br/>We travel along in our readings as Grant conquers his 17 victorious battles and we watch h</span>
  <span id="freeText13664657703874610917" style="display:none">My summer time BIG read is conquered. Hoorah! Book 2 of this exhaustive Civil War trilogy did not disappoint. Shelby Foote goes into extensive detail of many battles during years 3-4 of the war, with particular emphasis on the Battles of Vicksburg and Gettysburg. I especially enjoyed reading of the battle of Gettysburg, as I live in the area and frequently visit the historical sites there with my children. <br /><br />We travel along in our readings as Grant conquers his 17 victorious battles and we watch him rise to fame and prestige, causing Congress to reinstate the office of Lieutenant General of the Army held by only Washington before him. <br /><br />One can only learn of the heroic fortitude and “antique courage” necessary during these terrible times in our country’s history through the actions and words of several of the key players in this great civil war. Some are my favorite quotes are....<br /><br />“It is well that war is so terrible or we should grow too fond of it.” -Robert E. Lee<br /><br />“I desire to so conduct the affairs of this administration that if, at the end, when I come to lay down the reins of power, I have lost every other friend on earth, I shall at least have one friend left, and that friend shall be deep down inside of me.” -Ulysses S. Grant<br /><br />“We have not only an army to conquer. We have a state of mind to annihilate.” -Wendall Phillips. <br /><br />“Nothing touches the tired spot.” -Abraham Lincoln<br /><br />Highly recommend this series for anyone interested in our nations unadulterated and unfiltered war history. Those who do not learn from history are doomed to repeat it. Considering the heated politically correct time period we find ourselves living in, this narrative is timeless and essential. May we dig deep inside our hearts and find this well of courage and grit that our ancestors before us developed, to work towards creation of a more just and peaceful world. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13664657703874610917" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


