    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2115319474" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2115319474" />
    <a title="Alex" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6910620-alex"><img alt="Alex" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2115319474?book_show_action=true">Sep 16, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alex" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alex" href="/user/show/6910620-alex">Alex</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2115319474" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11586708190583021785">Foote&apos;s writing falls in an odd spot between history and entertainment; I guess that made him an obvious choice for his role in the Ken Burns Civil War documentary. Foote writes wonderfully, and though his status as a mid-century Southern white man shines through every word he does not indulge sectionalist perspectives the way many of the contemporaries did. As far as I know, Foote&apos;s telling of the major facts and events is still considered accurate and probably no one has done a better job of h</span>
  <span id="freeText11586708190583021785" style="display:none">Foote's writing falls in an odd spot between history and entertainment; I guess that made him an obvious choice for his role in the Ken Burns Civil War documentary. Foote writes wonderfully, and though his status as a mid-century Southern white man shines through every word he does not indulge sectionalist perspectives the way many of the contemporaries did. As far as I know, Foote's telling of the major facts and events is still considered accurate and probably no one has done a better job of humanizing and illustrating the conflict from the perspective of soldiers, particularly white southern soldiers. It's clear that Foote loves all the men who fought in this war, and admires Lincoln and Grant while not being blind to the sins of the South or the faults of the Confederate government and military. <br /><br />For such a very long "Narrative," however, Foote seems incredibly cramped compared to more recent scholarship. Though he doesn't indulge in any bullshit denying the centrality of slavery to the Civil War or other such self-gratifying Southern myths, he also doesn't do much to place the war in context. He talks about suffering on the home front, particularly in the deprived and decimated south, only as it pertains to the soldiers and politicians.<br /><br />In short, Foote should be read by people who are interested in not just the history of the Civil War but also in the historiography: This is how 20th Century white historians wrote about the war.<br /><br />Those looking for a more concise and yet more comprehensive view should look to James McPherson's "Battle Cry of Freedom," and those who are interested in the way civilians coped with the war and the way it changed American society should look to various books ("This Republic of Suffering," "Mothers of Invention") by Drew Gilpan Faust. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11586708190583021785" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

