  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4037789834" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4037789834" />
    <a title="H.R.R. Gorman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/107953091-h-r-r-gorman"><img alt="H.R.R. Gorman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577991483p2/107953091.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4037789834?book_show_action=true">Jun 26, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="H.R.R. Gorman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="H.R.R. Gorman" href="/user/show/107953091-h-r-r-gorman">H.R.R. Gorman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4037789834" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5517855508930211230">Ok, if you haven&apos;t read it yet, I encourage you to go back and read Part I of this series. It explains part of why this is going to be really screwed up.<br/><br/>Anyway, Foote continues to focus on the military aspects of the war in this second part of the book. His ability to make each battle crescendo to a climax and then sort out the results in a denouement remains fantastic. I&apos;m not actually certain all of his narrative comes from real documentation, but I do enjoy all the little details he includes.</span>
  <span id="freeText5517855508930211230" style="display:none">Ok, if you haven't read it yet, I encourage you to go back and read Part I of this series. It explains part of why this is going to be really screwed up.<br /><br />Anyway, Foote continues to focus on the military aspects of the war in this second part of the book. His ability to make each battle crescendo to a climax and then sort out the results in a denouement remains fantastic. I'm not actually certain all of his narrative comes from real documentation, but I do enjoy all the little details he includes. This book, probably even more so than the extremely detailed first volume, expands the strategies of each battle.<br /><br />This expansion and dramatization was nowhere more effective than with Chancellorsville. Chancellorsville, which is one of the boldest, audacious, and effective of Lee's victories, started the same as all the other battles. The Confederates, massively outgunned, outnumbered, starving, and naked, face their superior enemy with aplomb. Through what seems to be risky but carefully planned maneuvers planned by Lee and Jackson, a night attack turns the tide and the Union soldiers retreat. However, the battle comes at the cost of Jackson's arm and life.<br /><br />As I mentioned, though, this book is where we start to see the Southern military falling apart. With their ports effectively blockaded and Union soldiers coming at them from all sides, food and forage is scarce on all fronts. They have few guns, little clothing, and scant food, and even though they solidly whip the Union several times, they can ill afford the losses which the Union regularly sustains. It pains me to say that, militarily, the South feels like an underdog, which stories typically want you to root for.<br /><br />Now, here's the part which people will crucify me for:<br /><br />As I read it, the version of Lincoln shown in this book is not pleasant.<br /><br />I've never really studied Lincoln (you know you're raised "evil" white Southern as f*ck when your grandparents give you a fact poster of all the presidents and it includes Jefferson Davis). However, it's widely agreed that Lincoln is like #1 or #2 of all time President rankings. However, this book shows him to be... ineffective as a commander in chief. This is very evident in how he tells his generals to do stupid things to protect him in his capitol or to go off blindly attacking when the generals would be better off pursuing their other plans. He holds back a large force as a last-ditch guard at the capitol while his soldiers get fed into the meat grinder. He doesn't seem concerned with conscription. His political scheming seems extremely selfish, sometimes destructive. The thing which he does right - the Emancipation Proclamation - was well-written but effectively half-assed and with the intent of keeping Britain out of the war. He seems snitty, self-righteous, and kind of a bumbling fool when it comes to managing his army.<br /><br />In contrast to how Lincoln is presented, Jefferson Davis seems a bit more sympathetic (except that he owns slaves, which let's all agree is terrible). He's unquestionably better at operating his armies and is way, way better at handling all the military voices aimed at him. Whereas Lincoln fights all his commanders, Davis smoothly handles all the internal bickering. Davis fails, however, in terms of the political ring. He's not very personally likable, not very well-spoken, and is the head of a political construct that is extremely flawed. Any country that supports secession must, in turn, be subjected to that same problem.<br /><br />Anyway, by the end of the book you can see the writing on the wall. The soldiers of the South are just too far gone, and while Lincoln can just put out a call for more conscripts, the South has nothing left to give.<br /><br />Have you read this book? I'd love to hear from someone else who's gone through it. Am I just too inculcated with the Lost Cause Narrative, or did Foote portray Lincoln in the way I interpreted? God, please let me know if I'm too far gone.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5517855508930211230" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

